00:09:47,700 --> 00:09:49,000
Wait, wait,                     
wait, Fras.                     

242
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:50,800
You're not really               
gonna go in there               

243
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:52,400
and drink tea,                  
are ya?                         

244
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:54,800
Come on out here                
and sit at the bar,             

245
00:09:54,900 --> 00:09:57,800
you know,                       
with the guys.                  

246
00:09:57,900 --> 00:09:59,800
Have a beer.                    
            Yeah.               

247
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:04,300
Well, I guess I-I could.        

248
00:10:04,400 --> 00:10:05,700
                 (clears throat)

249
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:06,900
              No.               

250
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:11,500
I mean, you're-you're tellin' us
you're just gonna go back there 

251
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:14,300
     and sit with your wife     
    and sip tea, huh?           

252
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:16,500
        Yup, that's me.         

253
00:10:16,500 --> 00:10:19,200
Whipped and proud of it.        

254
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:24,600
Thank you.                      

255
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:25,800
         Here you are.          

256
00:10:25,900 --> 00:10:27,800
        Please allow me.        

257
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:32,400
    All right, there.           

258
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:34,000
 Now you'll notice on the menu  

259
00:10:34,100 --> 00:10:36,700
    that we have a...           
 a wide selection of sandwiches 

260
00:10:36,700 --> 00:10:41,300
    and delectables, and, uh,   
many, many varieties of tea.    

261
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:43,100
    So, what can I get you?     

262
00:10:43,200 --> 00:10:45,400
     Just some tea, please.     

263
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:49,200
      That's it? Just tea?      

264
00:10:49,400 --> 00:10:51,500
         Well, perhaps          
    I could tempt you           

265
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:53,700
         with some tiny         
      little sandwiches or      

266
00:10:53,800 --> 00:10:55,600
        fresh biscuits?         

267
00:10:56,900 --> 00:10:59,600
            Scones?             

268
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:01,600
 We're both watching our diets, 

269
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:04,400
  so two pots of Orange Pekoe   
        would be lovely.        

270
00:11:04,500 --> 00:11:05,600
FRASIER:                        
Hon,                            

271
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:06,700
  maybe we should split a pot.  

272
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:09,300
            Well...             

273
00:11:09,400 --> 00:11:12,700
 Per-Perhaps one of my slightly 
  more expensive herbal teas?   

274
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:14,200
Uh, no, thank you.              

275
00:11:14,300 --> 00:11:17,100
 You guys cannot just have tea. 

276
00:11:17,100 --> 00:11:18,300
                        Tea is a
                    loss leader.

277
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:20,500
          I lose money          
    just boiling the water.     

278
00:11:21,900 --> 00:11:22,900
    And, Lilith, look.          

279
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,100
      (blows through lips)      

280
00:11:24,200 --> 00:11:25,300
      You are hardly fat.       

281
00:11:25,400 --> 00:11:27,800
  You are borderline anorexic.  

282
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:29,600
Just                            

283
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:30,400
            pig out!            

284
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:31,900
  Order some strawberry tarts.  

285
00:11:31,900 --> 00:11:33,600
Strawberries make me break out. 

286
00:11:33,700 --> 00:11:36,400
  Well, at least that will put  
  a little color in your face.  

287
00:11:38,700 --> 00:11:40,800
        Perhaps we won't have   
                anything at all.

288
00:11:40,900 --> 00:11:42,000
             Fine!              

289
00:11:42,100 --> 00:11:44,000
 I don't really care. Get out!  

290
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:48,500
              Thanks for coming.
          Tell all your friends.

291
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:54,400
                Frasier, Lilith,
                  oh, I'm sorry.

292
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:56,400
                  I'm sorry. I'm
                 just desperate.

293
00:11:56,400 --> 00:11:58,200
    I don't understand          
        why nobody wants        

294
00:11:58,300 --> 00:12:00,100
            to come back into my
              beautiful tearoom.

295
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:02,100
Well, Rebecca,                  

296
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:05,100
a restaurant should be...       

297
00:12:05,200 --> 00:12:07,100
like a mistress.                

298
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:09,200
You see,                        

299
00:12:09,200 --> 00:12:13,200
one shouldn't feel that         
she's overeager to please.      

300
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:14,800
It's far more enticing          

301
00:12:14,900 --> 00:12:16,800
if you need her more            
than she needs you.             

302
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:21,600
            Who is this "she"   

303
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:23,600
                  you're talking
                 about, Frasier?

304
00:12:23,600 --> 00:12:25,600
Purely hypothetical.            

305
00:12:25,600 --> 00:12:26,900
                    Well, it's a
                  little strange

306
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:28,700
                for a happily   
                     married man

307
00:12:28,800 --> 00:12:30,500
              to go prattling on
            about a mistress.   

308
00:12:30,600 --> 00:12:32,000
Oh, come on, hon,               
give me this one.               

309
00:12:32,100 --> 00:12:33,500
You already heard me            
admit I was whipped             

310
00:12:33,500 --> 00:12:34,700
in front of the boys.           

311
00:12:34,800 --> 00:12:36,400
             That was good.     

312
00:12:40,300 --> 00:12:41,900
You were right, Sam.            

313
00:12:41,900 --> 00:12:43,200
Nobody's gonna come             
in here                         

314
00:12:43,200 --> 00:12:45,100
and have high tea               
and crumpets.                   

315
00:12:45,200 --> 00:12:46,500
                  Oh, don't give
                        up hope.

316
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:48,800
(Cockney accent):               
Maybe a carriage                
will break down                 

317
00:12:48,900 --> 00:12:51,700
in front of the pub             
and everyone'll come            
in for a cup of tea.            

318
00:12:51,800 --> 00:12:53,100
Have a cup of                   
tea, please.                    

319
00:12:53,100 --> 00:12:55,100
Have a cup of tea.              
                God, I hate you!

320
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:01,000
          Okay, guys.           

321
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:04,100
 Just made up a fresh new batch 
        of chili.               

322
00:13:04,200 --> 00:13:06,100
(cheering)                      

323
00:13:06,200 --> 00:13:07,800
                Now all I ask   

324
00:13:07,800 --> 00:13:09,500
         is you please          
    leave me some this time.    

325
00:13:12,400 --> 00:13:15,300
            You guys really like
          that chili, don't you?
  Mmm.                          

326
00:13:15,400 --> 00:13:16,800
                    Well, do you
                      think that

327
00:13:16,800 --> 00:13:20,000
          if I sold that kind of
    chili in my tearoom that,   

328
00:13:20,100 --> 00:13:21,700
                uh, I could make
                $500 a night?   

329
00:13:21,700 --> 00:13:22,400
Easy. But, uh,                  

330
00:13:22,600 --> 00:13:24,000
why would anyone want           
to go back there?               

331
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:26,500
We got a free pot               
of chili right here.            

332
00:13:26,500 --> 00:13:27,700
                Good point.     

333
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:29,800
     Chili in the tearoom!      

334
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:32,300
        Chili in the tearoom!   

335
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:36,200
Sammy, kiss that poolroom       
         good-bye, pal.         

336
00:13:48,300 --> 00:13:50,700
Sam, she's sellin' an awful     
lotta chili in there.           

337
00:13:50,800 --> 00:13:52,400
She must be gettin'             
pretty close                    

338
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:54,400
to that $500 mark.              
                    Oh, come on.

339
00:13:54,400 --> 00:13:55,900
              So she's sellin' a
                couple of bowls.

340
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,900
          I mean, how much chili
                  can a guy eat?

341
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:00,100
    Boy, I can't eat another    
        mouthful.               

342
00:14:00,200 --> 00:14:01,000
                     Uh-huh, see
                    what I mean?

343
00:14:01,100 --> 00:14:02,700
Thank goodness they sell        
these gallon buckets            

344
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:04,800
    for take-out.               

345
00:14:05,800 --> 00:14:07,600
            Oh, man,            

346
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:08,900
                  I'm gonna lose
                    my poolroom.

347
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:10,800
        I've gotta think of some
                way to stop her.

348
00:14:10,900 --> 00:14:11,900
I agree with you,               
Sammy.                          

349
00:14:11,900 --> 00:14:13,000
Go for the jugular.             

350
00:14:13,100 --> 00:14:13,900
                 Oh, yeah, yeah.

351
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:15,300
            Whatta ya mean, like
                sabotage her?   

352
00:14:15,400 --> 00:14:17,400
No, go for her jugular.         

353
00:14:18,300 --> 00:14:20,600
I mean, you can't               
sell chili                      

354
00:14:20,600 --> 00:14:22,700
when her throat's               
all ripped out.                 

355
00:14:22,800 --> 00:14:25,700
Well, she could,                
but who'd wanna buy it?         

356
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:28,700
                No, I got it,   
                    I got it.   

357
00:14:28,800 --> 00:14:30,800
             Let's call the fire
            marshal on her, huh?

358
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:32,800
                 No, no, no, no,
                     no, no, no,

359
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:34,100
                 that'd be below
                    the belt.   

360
00:14:34,200 --> 00:14:35,600
                I can't do that.

361
00:14:35,600 --> 00:14:37,400
Sam, can I talk to you a minute?

362
00:14:37,400 --> 00:14:39,700
                     You know, I
                just realized   

363
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:41,700
             that the closer I'm
             getting to my goal,

364
00:14:41,800 --> 00:14:43,700
    the more all I'm thinking   
            about is winning,   

365
00:14:43,800 --> 00:14:45,100
        and that's not right.   

366
00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:46,800
        I mean, I wasn't even   
      considering your feelings.

367
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:49,000
        You've had that poolroom
            for many, many years

368
00:14:49,100 --> 00:14:51,200
         and, well, I guess what
         I'm trying to say is...

369
00:14:51,300 --> 00:14:53,500
          (singsongy):          
      Ha-ha-ha-ha, <i>ha-ha!</i>       

370
00:14:53,500 --> 00:14:57,900
                I'm gonna win   
                  your poolroom!

371
00:15:01,300 --> 00:15:02,900
     Call the fire marshal!     

372
00:15:08,800 --> 00:15:11,000
 Glad that dinner rush is over. 

373
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:13,300
                 Give me time to
                put up a new pot

374
00:15:13,400 --> 00:15:15,700
        before the after-theatre
                crowd gets here.

375
00:15:15,800 --> 00:15:17,800
                 Sam, I'm takin'
                        a break.

376
00:15:17,900 --> 00:15:19,000
Me, too, Sammy.                 

377
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:21,000
I'm down to the last notch      
on my belt.                     

378
00:15:21,100 --> 00:15:23,500
        Yeah, I had to make a   
            new one with a nail.

379
00:15:25,300 --> 00:15:27,600
 Hey, Cliff, you got somethin'  
          in the mail.          

380
00:15:27,600 --> 00:15:29,300
    Huh?                        
That reminds me.                

381
00:15:29,400 --> 00:15:30,800
  Did I ever take you out back  

382
00:15:30,900 --> 00:15:33,100
  and kick the hell out of you  
for that postal increase?       

383
00:15:33,200 --> 00:15:34,400
    Uh-huh.                     

384
00:15:34,500 --> 00:15:35,200
             Good.              

385
00:15:35,300 --> 00:15:37,100
 Just goin' over my checklist.  

386
00:15:37,100 --> 00:15:39,300
        Well, look at this!     

387
00:15:39,400 --> 00:15:42,900
        It's a reply from my    
        Weathergirl Dorothy.    

388
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,200
Oh, look at that,               
the sweetheart.                 

389
00:15:45,200 --> 00:15:46,800
She sent a little photo         
of herself.                     

390
00:15:46,900 --> 00:15:48,300
            No, no, no, Cliffie,

391
00:15:48,300 --> 00:15:49,600
                I believe that's
            a satellite photo   

392
00:15:49,700 --> 00:15:52,600
                of the entire   
            Eastern Seaboard.   

393
00:15:52,700 --> 00:15:54,600
Oh, yeah,                       
but she's in there.             

394
00:15:54,700 --> 00:15:56,600
I mean, I'm in there.           

395
00:15:56,700 --> 00:15:59,200
We're all in there.             

396
00:15:59,200 --> 00:16:01,500
                The letter says,
                    "Dear Cliff,

397
00:16:01,500 --> 00:16:03,500
          "Thank you so much for
              your sweet letter.

398
00:16:03,600 --> 00:16:05,200
            "You did not mention
        what grade you're in,   

399
00:16:05,200 --> 00:16:06,600
    "but from the handwriting   
                         I guess

400
00:16:06,600 --> 00:16:10,100
              "that you're a big
                boy of 11 or 12.

401
00:16:10,100 --> 00:16:12,100
                 "Maybe when you
                        grow up,

402
00:16:12,100 --> 00:16:13,500
                "you can be a   
             weatherperson, too.

403
00:16:13,600 --> 00:16:16,300
                    Yours truly,
                Dorothy Borsik."

404
00:16:17,700 --> 00:16:19,500
            CARLA (whispers):   
                      Sammy, the
                fire marshal.   

405
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:20,900
Sam,                            

406
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,000
        we got a tip that Cheers
          is operating a kitchen

407
00:16:23,100 --> 00:16:24,700
            without a permit.   

408
00:16:24,800 --> 00:16:26,700
            Anything to that?   

409
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:28,400
          Oh, gosh no.          

410
00:16:28,500 --> 00:16:30,500
  I don't think anything that   
  would concern you, you know,  

411
00:16:30,500 --> 00:16:33,000
         just a couple          
of exposed propane tanks,       

412
00:16:33,100 --> 00:16:34,700
                    unventilated
                      hot plate.

413
00:16:34,800 --> 00:16:36,600
      I mean, but that...       
     oh, now wait a second.     

414
00:16:36,700 --> 00:16:39,600
         Gee, that's a,         
that's a potential fire hazard. 

415
00:16:39,700 --> 00:16:41,600
And you, you're a fire marshal. 

416
00:16:41,700 --> 00:16:43,200
      What was I thinking?      

417
00:16:44,700 --> 00:16:46,800
            I think I'll just   
                take a look-see.

418
00:16:49,900 --> 00:16:52,900
Maybe I shouldn't have called   
            the fire department.

419
00:16:52,900 --> 00:16:54,200
        Maybe that was wrong.   

420
00:16:54,300 --> 00:16:55,700
Don't chicken out               
now, Sam.                       

421
00:16:55,800 --> 00:16:57,500
                     No, no, no,
              maybe I shoulda...

422
00:16:57,500 --> 00:16:59,800
              put a mouse in the
            chili and called the
              health department.

423
00:16:59,900 --> 00:17:01,200
                 That would have
                been funnier.   

424
00:17:01,300 --> 00:17:03,300
        (laughing)              

425
00:17:03,400 --> 00:17:04,600
              Sam,              

426
00:17:04,700 --> 00:17:05,700
you should                      

427
00:17:05,700 --> 00:17:06,900
    be ashamed of yourself.     

428
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:08,400
Do you realize                  

429
00:17:08,500 --> 00:17:10,200
  everything that Rebecca has   
     attempted in her life      

430
00:17:10,300 --> 00:17:12,000
    has resulted in failure?    

431
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:12,700
             Yeah.              

432
00:17:12,900 --> 00:17:14,200
This is her first               

433
00:17:14,300 --> 00:17:16,700
success, and you're trying      
to take it away from her.       

434
00:17:16,800 --> 00:17:18,200
      That's my poolroom!       

435
00:17:18,200 --> 00:17:19,400
    But it's her life.          

436
00:17:19,400 --> 00:17:20,600
     But it's my poolroom.      

437
00:17:22,100 --> 00:17:24,000
 Come on, you guys, understand  
        that, don't ya?         

438
00:17:24,100 --> 00:17:26,000
                Yeah, Sam, we   
                     understand.

439
00:17:26,100 --> 00:17:28,600
We understand you made a fair   
        bet, you saw that you   

440
00:17:28,700 --> 00:17:30,300
                were gonna lose,
    and you started cheatin'.   

441
00:17:31,700 --> 00:17:33,700
Well, I-I-I didn't want         
to be a bad sport.              

442
00:17:33,800 --> 00:17:37,600
I just wanted to do anything    
I had to to win.                

443
00:17:37,700 --> 00:17:40,600
But that's no reason            
for you to be a cheater.        

444
00:17:40,700 --> 00:17:42,800
            But you were the one
        who told me to cheat!   

445
00:17:42,900 --> 00:17:45,000
No, I said                      
to kill her.                    

446
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:49,500
Cheating's wrong.               

447
00:17:51,300 --> 00:17:52,500
        I'm, I'm sorry.         

448
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:54,700
 What, do you all hate me now?  
          Is that...?           

449
00:17:54,700 --> 00:17:56,500
    Well, kinda, yeah.          

450
00:17:58,500 --> 00:18:00,800
          I'm afraid that's some
                list, Miss Howe.

451
00:18:00,900 --> 00:18:01,900
                        NORM:   
                          Great,

452
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:03,600
    now he's writin' her up     
          a citation.           

453
00:18:03,600 --> 00:18:06,400
                  So it's beans,
                tomato paste,   

454
00:18:06,500 --> 00:18:09,200
                 onions, peppers
                and ground beef.

455
00:18:09,300 --> 00:18:10,900
No, that's ground chuck.        

456
00:18:10,900 --> 00:18:13,900
            Oh, ground chuck.   

457
00:18:16,600 --> 00:18:17,800
                Serves eight?   
Uh-huh.                         

458
00:18:17,800 --> 00:18:19,900
What're you gonna do,           
share with the other guys       

459
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:21,500
at the firehouse?               
                Why should I?   

460
00:18:21,600 --> 00:18:23,500
             What have they ever
                    done for me?

461
00:18:25,300 --> 00:18:26,900
        Sam,                    

462
00:18:26,900 --> 00:18:28,500
why do you suppose              

463
00:18:28,500 --> 00:18:30,500
          the fire marshal would
        come by my chili room   

464
00:18:30,500 --> 00:18:32,200
                     tonight, of
                     all nights?

465
00:18:32,300 --> 00:18:35,500
            Kismet?             

466
00:18:35,600 --> 00:18:37,800
                 No, because you
                 tipped him off.

467
00:18:37,900 --> 00:18:40,100
Sam, you could've               
gotten me shut down.            

468
00:18:40,100 --> 00:18:43,800
             Thank God that dear
            man loves his chili.

469
00:18:43,800 --> 00:18:44,800
        I'm sorry.              

470
00:18:44,900 --> 00:18:46,100
             I got carried away.

471
00:18:46,100 --> 00:18:47,300
            Yes, you did.       

472
00:18:47,400 --> 00:18:49,300
              Listen, I, I gotta
            make this up to you.

473
00:18:49,300 --> 00:18:51,800
              How, how, how, how
                close are you   

474
00:18:51,900 --> 00:18:53,600
        to getting that $500?   

475
00:18:53,600 --> 00:18:54,700
                      About $20.

476
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:55,600
             I'll tell you what.

477
00:18:55,700 --> 00:18:56,800
             Let me, let me, uh,

478
00:18:56,900 --> 00:18:59,500
                buy a bowl of   
                  chili for $20.
No.                             

479
00:18:59,500 --> 00:19:01,000
              No, Sam, you don't
                need to do that.

480
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:03,000
No, listen, I wanna prove to you
that I'm not a poor loser.      

481
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:04,100
                Come on, give me

482
00:19:04,200 --> 00:19:04,800
     my bowl of chili here.     

