        Thank you, Sam,         
      this is nice of you.      

484
00:19:07,300 --> 00:19:09,500
Go ahead,                       
just put on Woody's hat         

485
00:19:09,600 --> 00:19:10,700
and get the chili yourself      

486
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:12,700
because I want to get           
my camera and get a picture     

487
00:19:12,700 --> 00:19:14,000
of you pouring                  
that bowl                       

488
00:19:14,100 --> 00:19:15,600
      of chili that put me      
         over the top.          

489
00:19:15,700 --> 00:19:17,100
Oh, you got                     
to warm it up, Sam.             

490
00:19:17,200 --> 00:19:18,800
You know how to                 
turn on the flame?              

491
00:19:18,800 --> 00:19:19,800
It's kind of tricky.            

492
00:19:19,800 --> 00:19:21,600
                      Yeah, I'll
                  figure it out.

493
00:19:23,400 --> 00:19:27,000
                (loud explosion)

494
00:19:27,100 --> 00:19:30,100
            Yep, that's how I   
            figured it out, too.

495
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:45,300
    It was a accident.          

496
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:49,300
Sammy, are you okay?            

497
00:19:49,300 --> 00:19:52,300
You ever had a pot of chili fly 
          by your face          

498
00:19:52,300 --> 00:19:54,000
     at the speed of light?     

499
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:55,200
        No.                     

500
00:19:55,300 --> 00:19:57,400
             Don't.             

501
00:19:57,500 --> 00:20:00,300
                Look at the hole
                in that wall.   

502
00:20:00,400 --> 00:20:01,800
      Who could miss it, huh?   

503
00:20:01,800 --> 00:20:03,000
No, I'm talking                 
about the brick wall            

504
00:20:03,100 --> 00:20:05,600
            across the alley.   

505
00:20:05,700 --> 00:20:07,900
    Man, that pressure cooker   
      really wanted out of here.

506
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:10,900
Okay, everybody                 
out of here, out.               

507
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:13,400
Come on,                        
everybody, out!                 

508
00:20:13,400 --> 00:20:14,900
Go back to the bar,             
please.                         

509
00:20:14,900 --> 00:20:17,200
            Not you.            

510
00:20:17,300 --> 00:20:19,700
I want to talk to you.          

511
00:20:19,700 --> 00:20:24,500
  Don't you think maybe I should
    go to a trauma center first?

512
00:20:24,600 --> 00:20:27,000
                  S-Some of this
                    could be me.

513
00:20:29,900 --> 00:20:31,800
        Oh, come on, I know what
        you're thinking here,   

514
00:20:31,900 --> 00:20:33,800
    but I-I didn't do           
        this on purpose.        

515
00:20:33,900 --> 00:20:36,700
    I swear to God I didn't     
    do it on purpose.           

516
00:20:36,700 --> 00:20:38,200
    You did it just because     
  I started doing really well   

517
00:20:38,300 --> 00:20:39,300
 back here and you're jealous.  

518
00:20:39,300 --> 00:20:41,200
Y-You're just a big baby.       

519
00:20:41,300 --> 00:20:43,000
        I am not.               
                Yes, you are.   

520
00:20:43,100 --> 00:20:45,500
  You want everything for you   
      and nothing for me.       

521
00:20:45,500 --> 00:20:48,400
  Well, yeah, if that's being   
    a big baby, okay,           

522
00:20:48,500 --> 00:20:50,300
    but... but I'm a,           

523
00:20:50,400 --> 00:20:51,100
I'm a guy.                      

524
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:53,500
I'm supposed                    
to be a big baby.               

525
00:20:53,600 --> 00:20:54,600
      And you're a woman.       

526
00:20:54,700 --> 00:20:56,700
You know, you're supposed       
to be like a nice mommy         

527
00:20:56,800 --> 00:21:00,200
and tell me everything's okay   
and, and pat me on the head.    

528
00:21:00,300 --> 00:21:04,900
         I would like to pat you
      on the head with a pickax.

529
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:06,300
Oh, I, I know how you feel.     

530
00:21:06,400 --> 00:21:07,300
            I mean,             

531
00:21:07,400 --> 00:21:08,300
I'm sorry.                      

532
00:21:08,400 --> 00:21:10,100
             This is crazy, I...

533
00:21:10,200 --> 00:21:12,300
        I feel so sorry.        

534
00:21:12,400 --> 00:21:13,800
         No, you don't.         

535
00:21:13,800 --> 00:21:15,200
    Yes, I do, I really do.     

536
00:21:15,200 --> 00:21:16,300
     I just feel terrible.      

537
00:21:16,400 --> 00:21:19,700
  I... feel like I could cry.   

538
00:21:19,700 --> 00:21:22,600
             Okay.              

539
00:21:22,600 --> 00:21:24,000
        Okay what?              

540
00:21:25,500 --> 00:21:26,800
                Cry.            

541
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,100
What do you mean?               

542
00:21:29,200 --> 00:21:31,800
    I mean, make water come     
    out of your eyes.           

543
00:21:33,600 --> 00:21:35,200
    And that way I will know    
that you are really sorry       

544
00:21:35,300 --> 00:21:37,200
for what you've done here.      

545
00:21:38,100 --> 00:21:40,900
         Just cry?              

546
00:21:40,900 --> 00:21:41,600
                Yep.            

547
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,200
Does it count if, you know,     

548
00:21:56,300 --> 00:21:58,400
if you really want to cry,      
but you can't?                  

549
00:21:58,500 --> 00:21:59,500
                 No.            

550
00:21:59,500 --> 00:22:00,800
              Cry, Sam.         

551
00:22:00,900 --> 00:22:01,900
        Huh.                    

552
00:22:01,900 --> 00:22:04,900
(mock sobbing)                  

553
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:08,300
                      No onions.

554
00:22:09,300 --> 00:22:11,000
        I want real tears.      
             Now, just cry.     

555
00:22:11,100 --> 00:22:12,800
Give me a break.                
What am I supposed to--?        

556
00:22:12,900 --> 00:22:13,900
      I mean, isn't this enough?

557
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:16,300
                    A guy, a guy
                  who can't cry?

558
00:22:16,400 --> 00:22:17,700
                 I mean, that is
                  heartbreaking.

559
00:22:17,800 --> 00:22:21,100
Honey, there's nothing sadder   
than a man who can't cry.       

560
00:22:21,200 --> 00:22:22,500
                        No, Sam.

561
00:22:22,500 --> 00:22:23,700
         It is not enough.      

562
00:22:25,100 --> 00:22:28,500
            Wait, maybe I can   
              help you out here.

563
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:39,100
                (glass breaking)

564
00:22:39,200 --> 00:22:40,400
                      (footsteps
                    approaching)

565
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:42,200
             There.             

566
00:22:42,300 --> 00:22:43,800
         Now we can go.         

567
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:46,100
            Come on.            

568
00:22:46,200 --> 00:22:47,100
            What was that sound?

569
00:22:47,200 --> 00:22:48,300
Oh, that was the sound          

570
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:50,700
of me breaking all the windows  
out of your Corvette.           

571
00:22:50,800 --> 00:22:52,500
         (Sam sobbing)          

572
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:55,200
REBECCA:                        
There, now there                
are those tears.                

